04845nam a22006615i 9780226476438DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019016538  a97802264764387 a10.7208/97802264764382doi  a(DE-B1597)568309  a(OCoLC)1198929362  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHT175b.S265 2019 4aHT175b.S265 2019 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a307.7609732231 aSchuerman, Matthew L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNewcomers :bGentrification and Its Discontents /cMatthew L. Schuerman. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b21 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart Is: Beginnings, 1956– 1978 -- tOne. The Demise of Urban Renewal -- tTwo. Back to the City: New York City, 1963– 1978 -- tThree. Geography Is Destiny: San Francisco, 1966– 1980 -- tFour. The Gold Coast and the Slum, Revisited: Chicago, 1966– 1991 -- tPart Two: RECKONING, 1972– 2000 -- tFive. Cassandras: 1972– 1981 -- tSix. Adaptive Reuse: New York and Chicago, 1975– 1997 -- tSeven. Supply and Demand: San Francisco, 1981– 2000 -- tEight. The Rise and Fall of Rent Control -- tPart Three. CONFLICT, 1992– 2018 -- tNine. Mixed- Income Mixed Blessings: Chicago, 1992– 2014 -- tTen. Zero-Sum Game: San Francisco, 2001– 2018 -- tEleven. 300 Nassau Avenue: New York City, 2004– 2016 -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGentrification is transforming cities, small and large, across the country. Though it’s easy to bemoan the diminished social diversity and transformation of commercial strips that often signify a gentrifying neighborhood, determining who actually benefits and who suffers from this nebulous process can be much harder. The full story of gentrification is rooted in large-scale social and economic forces as well as in extremely local specifics—in short, it’s far more complicated than both its supporters and detractors allow. In Newcomers, journalist Matthew L. Schuerman explains how a phenomenon that began with good intentions has turned into one of the most vexing social problems of our time. He builds a national story using focused histories of northwest Brooklyn, San Francisco’s Mission District, and the onetime site of Chicago’s Cabrini-Green housing project, revealing both the commonalities among all three and the place-specific drivers of change. Schuerman argues that gentrification has become a too-easy flashpoint for all kinds of quasi-populist rage and pro-growth boosterism. In Newcomers, he doesn’t condemn gentrifiers as a whole, but rather articulates what it is they actually do, showing not only how community development can turn foul, but also instances when a “better” neighborhood truly results from changes that are good. Schuerman draws no easy conclusions, using his keen reportorial eye to create sharp, but fair, portraits of the people caught up in gentrification, the people who cause it, and its effects on the lives of everyone who calls a city home.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCities and townszUnited States. 0aGentrificationzCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aGentrificationzIllinoiszChicago. 0aGentrificationzNew York (State)zNew York. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aBrooklyn.  aChicago.  aGentrification.  aSan Francisco.  acities.  acommunity.  adisplacement.  aneighborhood.  areal estate.  asuburbs.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071194340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226476438423Coveruhtt